                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <placeName>Kingston Jamaica</placeName>
                                        <date>Rosh hodesh</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <date>Sivan 5611.</date>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="align(right)">
                                        <date>Sunday June 11th</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Revd I Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">Respected Friend</p>
                              <p rend="indent(4)">Your favor of <date>May 6th</date><lb/> came duly
                                        to hand giving much regret at<lb/> the ingratitude practiced
                                        towards you. But<lb/> you have that written which must
                                        baffle all<lb/> all the efforts of your enemies; the
                                        cannot<lb/> eqult<add>?</add> long and in their exultation
                                        of (what<lb/> they may <hi rend="underline">term</hi> your
                                        defeat) they must be<lb/> condemned by the <add>?</add> and
                                        more enlight-<lb/>ened portion of the world to which
                                        your<lb/> devotion to their service has been known<lb/> I
                                        trust that your literary efforts will meet<lb/> with more
                                                  <hi rend="underline">praising</hi><add>?</add>
                                        encouragement<lb/> than they do here: the few readers there
                                        are<lb/> are unwilling to pay for knowledge, in<lb/> part,
                                        with few exceptions, they are not a<lb/> people to be
                                        depended on. <persName>Mr Laruton</persName> has<lb/>
                                        changed his mind on his contemplated visit<lb/> to the
                                                  <placeName>States</placeName>; he, <add>?</add>
                                        your parcel but as the</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>Postage was high 8/ he allowed them to remain<lb/> there on for
                                        aught he knows may have<lb/> been taken home again, if this
                                        be proper<lb/> agency, I am quite mistaken, I believe
                                        he<lb/> was not <hi rend="underline">in friends</hi> not
                                        having received anything<lb/> for you. I showed him your
                                        letter to which<lb/> he replied that he could sell as many
                                        of your<lb/> works (naming the purchasers) as to remit<lb/>
                                        you $80. but could not under sell them<lb/> without your
                                        sanction. I requested him to<lb/> communicate the same to
                                        you by the<lb/> Steamer; but fearing he has not done so;
                                        I<lb/> feel it necessary to make you acquainted with<lb/>
                                        it. According to his account the books are somewhat<lb/>
                                        injured; my advice would be to take what you<lb/> can get
                                        for them, and after that charge your full<lb/> price for new
                                        ones. Great complaint at the high<lb/> price of your
                                        publications I friend to literature<lb/> told me that he
                                        thought you would <del>effect</del> confer<lb/> more benefit
                                                  <del>to</del> on yourself and the public<lb/> by
                                        sending out your magazines in the way that<lb/>
                                        <placeName>Chambers</placeName> does. Let them be sold by
                                        numbers</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>people will gratify a fancy and pay more in a<lb/> small way, than
                                        subscribing to an entire work<lb/> such is the mean spirit
                                        of this place, though<lb/> I do fortunately meet in my
                                                  <add>?</add> with a<lb/> few expressions. My
                                        literary friend would<lb/> rather feast on a good
                                        substantial work<lb/> than all the dainties of the universe.
                                        In<lb/> fact were it not for his librarying<lb/> mind (to
                                        use your own adage) would long<lb/> since have gone to vast
                                        so much am I indebt-<lb/>ed to my friend <persName>Mr Heyman
                                                  Cohen Del<add>?</add></persName>;<lb/> a young
                                        gentleman of good parts; clear mind<lb/> and would by little
                                        practice be a fine lec-<lb/>turer; <add>?</add> for the
                                        world he is only the merchant.<lb/> I should like to hear
                                        some publications of<lb/> your honorable successor
                                                  <persName>Mr. Morais.</persName> How<lb/> strange
                                        it will appear to me should I reform,<lb/> to see another
                                        occupying your place. <persName>Louisa</persName><lb/> seems
                                        to regret much the state of affairs<lb/> when she last
                                        wrote. <persName>Mrs H</persName> has not said<lb/> anything
                                        on the subject but that was owing<lb/> to the melancholy
                                        state of my feelings. I regret<lb/> exceedingly you did not
                                        know the date of</p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>my misfortune <add>?</add> it was on the <date>8th Thebet<lb/> at
                                                  eleven o clock</date>
                                        <add>?</add> a sad month indeed to me, the loss of a parent
                                        at<lb/> any time is a painful event in ones life, and
                                        when<lb/> attended with so much attachment, so much to<lb/>
                                        render life desirable, tis indeed <add>?</add> more so.<lb/>
                                        Piety charity <del>were</del> and a firmness in the
                                        faith<lb/> of her fathers were predominant may you
                                        ex<lb/>plain and widow shared<add>?</add> her smallest
                                        stores. A<lb/> most tender affectionate mother; for two
                                        days, all<lb/> she said was poor <add>?</add>, poor
                                                  <add>?</add> till too<lb/> weak to speak such was
                                        her ardent love for<lb/> me, I really feel, my friend that
                                        some great offence<lb/> on my part only could have brought
                                        down<lb/> the anger of Heaven on me in this bereavement<lb/>
                                        I feel that the one I loved most on earth in bloom<lb/> and
                                                  <add>?</add> notwithstanding her <del>to</del> age
                                        63, to be thus<lb/> snatched from me when least expected, is
                                        a trial<lb/> almost more than I can bear, yet tis the
                                        Divine<lb/> hand and I could subscribe the more <add>?</add>
                                        aiding<lb/> mind not run this constantly or my having it as
                                        a<lb/> punishment; perhaps I did not deserve such an<lb/>
                                        angel; yes, <persName>David</persName>
                                        <add>?</add> will tell you of her<lb/> virtues. O! how
                                        fervently do I pray that should it</p>
